Temporary variable of the expression that implemented a Drop trait, causing a lifetime check error.

I tried this code:
```
struct MyStruct {
    data: String
}
struct MyResult<'a> {
    data: &'a str
}

impl MyStruct {
    fn foo<'a>(&'a self) -> Result<MyResult<'a>,()> {
        Ok(MyResult {
            data: &self.data
        })
    }
}

//implement Drop for MyResult
impl<'a> Drop for MyResult<'a> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        println!("drop MyResult");
    }
}

fn main() {
    let st = MyStruct { data: String::from("abcd") };
    if let Ok(_) = st.foo() {
    }
}
```

I expected to see this happen: 
no error

Instead, this happened: 
```
error[E0597]: `st` does not live long enough
  --> src/main.rs:23:20
   |
23 |     if let Ok(_) = st.foo() {
   |                    ^^------
   |                    |
   |                    borrowed value does not live long enough
   |                    a temporary with access to the borrow is created here ...
24 |     }
25 | }
   | -
   | |
   | `st` dropped here while still borrowed
   | ... and the borrow might be used here, when that temporary is dropped and runs the destructor for type `std::result::Result<MyResult<'_>, ()>`
   |
   = note: The temporary is part of an expression at the end of a block. Consider adding semicolon after the expression so its temporaries are dropped sooner, before the local variables declared by the block are dropped.
```

